Pneumonia Detection using ViT and EfficientNet with Explainability¶

This notebook implements a Vision Transformer-based model (Hugging Face TFViTModel) to detect pneumonia from chest X-ray images. It includes training, evaluation, and explainable AI (XAI) analysis using Grad-CAM.

Dataset: Kaggle Chest X-ray Pneumonia

Pneumonia is an inflammatory condition primarily affecting the alveoli, the microscopic air sacs within the lungs.It usually manifests as fever dyspnea chest pain and a cough that can be dry or productive to start. People can differ greatly in how severe their pneumonia is. The condition can also be caused by fungal organisms certain medications or underlying medical conditions such as autoimmune diseases although bacterial and viral pathogens are the most common causes. A number of conditions such as asthma diabetes mellitus congestive heart failure chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD) immunosuppression a history of smoking and an impaired cough reflex (e. g. G. following a stroke) as well as hereditary conditions like cystic fibrosis. Diagnostic instruments like sputum cultures blood tests and chest radiography may be used to support the diagnosis which is frequently based on clinical evaluation and physical examination. Clinically pneumonia is divided into three categories: community-acquired hospital-acquired and healthcare-associated.¶

def create_dataframe_from_directory(directory):
    filepaths, labels = [], []
    for label in os.listdir(directory):
        path = os.path.join(directory, label)
        for file in os.listdir(path):
            filepaths.append(os.path.join(path, file))
            labels.append(label)
    return pd.DataFrame({'filepath': filepaths, 'label': labels})

base_path = 'C:/Users/jiver/Downloads/CHEST/chest_xray'
df_train = create_dataframe_from_directory(os.path.join(base_path, 'train'))
df_val = create_dataframe_from_directory(os.path.join(base_path, 'val'))
df_test = create_dataframe_from_directory(os.path.join(base_path, 'test'))

IMAGE_SIZE = (224, 224)
BATCH_SIZE = 32
SEED = 123

data_augmentation = tf.keras.Sequential([
    layers.RandomFlip("horizontal"),
    layers.RandomRotation(0.1),       
    layers.RandomZoom(0.2),
    layers.RandomTranslation(0.1, 0.1)
])


train_ds = tf.keras.utils.image_dataset_from_directory(
    os.path.join(base_path, "train"),
    validation_split=0.1,
    subset="training",
    seed=SEED,
    image_size=IMAGE_SIZE,
    batch_size=BATCH_SIZE
)

val_ds = tf.keras.utils.image_dataset_from_directory(
    os.path.join(base_path, "train"),
    validation_split=0.1,
    subset="validation",
    seed=SEED,
    image_size=IMAGE_SIZE,
    batch_size=BATCH_SIZE
)

test_ds = tf.keras.utils.image_dataset_from_directory(
    os.path.join(base_path, "test"),
    seed=SEED,
    image_size=IMAGE_SIZE,
    batch_size=BATCH_SIZE
)

# Save the class names BEFORE applying .map()
class_names = train_ds.class_names 

#  Class names
class_names = train_ds.class_names

#  Normalize and augment
train_ds = train_ds.map(lambda x, y: (data_augmentation(x, training=True) / 255.0, y))
val_ds = val_ds.map(lambda x, y: (x / 255.0, y))
test_ds = test_ds.map(lambda x, y: (x / 255.0, y))

#  Prefetch for performance
AUTOTUNE = tf.data.AUTOTUNE
train_ds = train_ds.prefetch(buffer_size=AUTOTUNE)
val_ds = val_ds.prefetch(buffer_size=AUTOTUNE)
test_ds = test_ds.prefetch(buffer_size=AUTOTUNE)

def show_image_samples(dataset, class_names):
    for images, labels in dataset.take(1):
        plt.figure(figsize=(10, 5))

        ax1 = plt.subplot(1, 2, 1)
        plt.imshow(images[0].numpy().squeeze(), cmap='gray')
        plt.title(class_names[labels[0]])
        plt.axis("off")

        ax2 = plt.subplot(1, 2, 2)
        plt.imshow(images[-1].numpy().squeeze(), cmap='gray')
        plt.title(class_names[labels[-1]])
        plt.axis("off")

    plt.suptitle("Example Images from Training Set")
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()


# Call the function
show_image_samples(train_ds, class_names)

The two sample X-ray images shown represent different classes within the dataset. Each image is rendered in grayscale and normalized for model input.

Vision Transformer Model Training¶

In [22]:
class ViTWrapper(layers.Layer):
    def __init__(self, vit_model, **kwargs):
        super().__init__(**kwargs)
        self.vit_model = vit_model

    def call(self, inputs):
        inputs = tf.transpose(inputs, perm=[0, 3, 1, 2])
        return self.vit_model(pixel_values=inputs).last_hidden_state

base_model = TFViTModel.from_pretrained('google/vit-base-patch16-224-in21k')
for layer in base_model.layers:
    layer.trainable = False

input_layer = keras.Input(shape=(224, 224, 3))
x = ViTWrapper(base_model)(input_layer)
x = layers.GlobalAveragePooling1D()(x)
x = layers.BatchNormalization()(x)
x = layers.Dropout(0.45)(x)
x = layers.Dense(220, activation='relu')(x)
x = layers.Dropout(0.25)(x)
x = layers.Dense(60, activation='relu')(x)
output_layer = layers.Dense(1, activation='sigmoid')(x)

model = keras.Model(inputs=input_layer, outputs=output_layer)
model.compile(optimizer=Adamax(learning_rate=0.001), loss='binary_crossentropy', metrics=['accuracy'])

early_stopping = EarlyStopping(monitor='val_loss', patience=10, restore_best_weights=True)

history = model.fit(train_ds, validation_data=val_ds, epochs=50, callbacks=[early_stopping])

All PyTorch model weights were used when initializing TFViTModel.

All the weights of TFViTModel were initialized from the PyTorch model.
If your task is similar to the task the model of the checkpoint was trained on, you can already use TFViTModel for predictions without further training.

The two plots above illustrate the model’s learning dynamics during training¶

Left Plot: Training vs Validation Accuracy¶

  • The model shows a rapid increase in accuracy within the first few epochs, quickly surpassing 90%.
  • Validation accuracy consistently exceeds training accuracy, indicating strong generalization without signs of overfitting.
  • After epoch 10, accuracy continues to improve gradually, eventually stabilizing around 97% for validation and 93% for training.

Right Plot: Training vs Validation Loss¶

  • Both training and validation loss drop sharply within the first 5 epochs, suggesting that the model quickly learns the core features.
  • Validation loss remains lower than training loss throughout, which is rare and indicates a well-regularized model.
  • There is no divergence between training and validation curves, showing no overfitting.

Overall Interpretation¶

  • The model is learning effectively and generalizing well
  • The gap where validation performance exceeds training performance may result from the use of dropout, batch normalization, or data augmentation, which are active only during training.
  • The training has converged smoothly, and the final metrics indicate high classification performance on unseen data.

Test-Time Augmentation¶

In [24]:
def predict_with_tta(model, dataset, augment_fn, num_augments=5):
    y_true, y_preds = [], []
    for images, labels in dataset:
        aug_preds = []
        for _ in range(num_augments):
            aug_images = augment_fn(images)
            aug_preds.append(model.predict(aug_images))
        avg_preds = np.mean(aug_preds, axis=0)
        y_preds.extend((avg_preds > 0.5).astype(int).flatten())
        y_true.extend(labels.numpy())
    return np.array(y_true), np.array(y_preds)

@tf.function
def horizontal_flip(images):
    return tf.image.random_flip_left_right(images)

y_true_tta, y_pred_tta = predict_with_tta(model, test_ds, horizontal_flip)
print("TTA Classification Report:\n", classification_report(y_true_tta, y_pred_tta))

Confusion Matrix Analysis¶

The confusion matrix provides a detailed breakdown of classification performance:

  • True Positives (Pneumonia correctly predicted): 387

  • True Negatives (Normal correctly predicted): 156

  • False Positives (Normal misclassified as Pneumonia): 78

  • False Negatives (Pneumonia misclassified as Normal): 3

The model demonstrates excellent sensitivity (recall) for detecting pneumonia, with only 3 missed cases out of 390.¶
However, the number of false positives (78) suggests that some normal chest X-rays are being incorrectly flagged as pneumonia.¶
While this conservative behavior helps avoid missed pneumonia cases, it may lead to unnecessary clinical interventions or anxiety.¶
To further improve, the next step should focus on increasing specificity — reducing false positives — without compromising sensitivity.¶

  • AUC = 0.83, indicating the model has an 83% probability of correctly distinguishing a randomly chosen positive (pneumonia) case from a negative (normal) one.

  • AUC values range from 0.5 (no discrimination) to 1.0 (perfect discrimination). An AUC of 0.83 represents strong discriminatory ability.

  • The ROC curve lies well above the diagonal baseline, demonstrating that the model performs significantly better than random guessing.

  • The shape of the curve shows that the model maintains a good balance between sensitivity (true positive rate) and specificity (false positive control).

  • Conclusion: The ViT model demonstrates reliable classification performance on chest X-rays, effectively identifying pneumonia cases while keeping false alarms under control.

Misclassified Examples¶

Below are some misclassified chest X-ray samples from the test set. These help us understand the visual limitations of the model:

  • Several Normal cases were misclassified as Pneumonia (e.g., True: 0 – Pred: 1). This may result from subtle patterns like faint shadows, rib overlaps, or poor contrast, which can mimic pathological signs and confuse the model.

  • Some Pneumonia cases, although correctly predicted (True: 1 – Pred: 1), show only mild opacities or ambiguous features. These borderline examples highlight the model’s reliance on non-obvious cues, potentially overfitting to texture or edge variations rather than clear diagnostic signs.

  • These cases reinforce the need for Explainable AI (XAI) tools like Grad-CAM or attention maps, to better understand which regions influenced the prediction, and whether the model's focus aligns with clinical reasoning.

Misclassifications are often tied to subtle visual artifacts or ambiguity, underscoring the importance of both data quality and model interpretability when deploying AI in medical diagnostics.¶

def preprocess(ds):
    return ds.map(lambda x, y: (preprocess_input(x), y))

eff_train = preprocess(train_ds)
eff_val = preprocess(val_ds)
eff_test = preprocess(test_ds)

def get_grad_cam(model, image, inner_layer_name='block7a_project_bn'):
    # Extract the EfficientNetB0 base model
    backbone = model.get_layer("efficientnetb0")

    # Get input + output from the inner backbone directly
    grad_model = tf.keras.models.Model(
        inputs=backbone.input,
        outputs=[backbone.get_layer(inner_layer_name).output, backbone.output]
    )

    # Run Grad-CAM
    with tf.GradientTape() as tape:
        conv_outputs, predictions = grad_model(image)
        class_idx = tf.argmax(predictions[0])
        loss = predictions[:, class_idx]

    grads = tape.gradient(loss, conv_outputs)
    pooled_grads = tf.reduce_mean(grads, axis=(0, 1, 2))
    cam = conv_outputs[0] @ pooled_grads[..., tf.newaxis]
    cam = tf.squeeze(cam)

    cam = tf.maximum(cam, 0)
    cam /= tf.reduce_max(cam)
    cam = tf.image.resize(cam[..., tf.newaxis], image.shape[1:3])
    return cam.numpy()

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import matplotlib.cm as cm

def show_effnet_attention_overlay(image_tensor, heatmap, title="EfficientNet Grad-CAM"):
    import cv2
    import numpy as np
    import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

    # Remove batch and convert to numpy
    image = image_tensor[0].numpy()  # (224, 224, 3)

    # Normalize image
    image = (image - image.min()) / (image.max() - image.min())

    # Prepare heatmap
    heatmap = cv2.resize(heatmap, (image.shape[1], image.shape[0]))
    heatmap = cv2.applyColorMap(np.uint8(255 * heatmap), cv2.COLORMAP_JET)
    overlay = cv2.addWeighted(np.uint8(image * 255), 1 - 0.4, heatmap, 0.4, 0)

    # Predict label + confidence
    probs = eff_model.predict(image_tensor)
    label = class_names[tf.argmax(probs[0])]
    confidence = tf.reduce_max(probs[0])

    # Show image
    plt.figure(figsize=(6, 6))
    plt.imshow(overlay)
    plt.axis("off")
    plt.title(f"{title}\nPredicted: {label} ({confidence:.2%})")
    plt.show()

This Grad-CAM visualization illustrates the regions of the chest X-ray that had the strongest influence on the EfficientNetB0 model’s decision to classify the input as NORMAL, with high confidence (93.71%).

  • The highlighted regions (yellow and red) indicate where the model focused most when making its classification decision. These areas contribute most significantly to the model’s output.

The lack of strong activations in abnormal patterns suggests the model detected no pathological signs consistent with pneumonia.

  • The confidence score and focus distribution imply the model found anatomical patterns consistent with healthy lung structures.

  • This interpretability helps verify that the model’s decision aligns with medically relevant features, increasing trust in its predictions — particularly important for clinical decision support.
